JOHANNESBURG - The Social Security Agency of SA (Sassa) has approached the Constitutional Court to ensure that social grants will be paid on 1 April.READ: Grants crisis before parliamentary watchdogIt's asking the court to extend the current contract with Cash Paymaster Services (CPS) for another year.Sassa was grilled by Parliament's public accounts committee on Tuesday morning about its failure to find a new payer.Programme manager Zodwa Mvulane told Parliament they were meeting CPS only on Wednesday to negotiate an extension of the existing contract.READ: No programme in place to deliver Sassa grantsThe delay could jeopardise the payment of 17-million social grants.Adding to its woes, the Black Sash Trust has now launched a Constitutional Court application against Sassa to protect social grants.eNCA's Annika Larsen gives more insight into the issue: eNCA